      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou1-tc",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions acceptance criteria — MRL 2",
        "description": "Experimental boundary conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid viscosity) must be measured with calibrated instruments traceable to NIST standards. Measurement uncertainty must be reported for each condition."
      },
      "rationale": "All five operating points were tested using calibrated Coriolis flow meters (±0.5% reading, NIST-traceable) and optical tachometers (±0.1% reading). Fluid viscosity was measured at test temperature with a cone-plate rheometer. Measurement uncertainty is fully reported in the test report TR-GCBP-2024-03."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-oc",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou1-oc",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criteria — MRL 2",
        "description": "Relative hemolysis index (RH) predicted by CFD must agree with bench measurements within the combined experimental and simulation uncertainty band (coverage factor k=2) at all 5 operating points."
      },
      "rationale": "At operating point OP-4 (6 L/min, 3500 RPM), the CFD-predicted RH of 1.09 falls outside the k=2 combined uncertainty band of the bench measurement (RH = 0.91 ± 0.07 at 95% CI, expanded to ±0.14 at k=2, yielding an upper bound of 1.05). The 0.04 exceedance is marginal but consistent across three independent mesh realisations, ruling out numerical noise as the cause. The factor achievedLevel (1) is therefore below the requiredLevel (2). No offset rationale is claimed."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-rqi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou1-rqi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Relevance of QoI acceptance criteria — MRL 2",
        "description": "The computational QoI (volume-averaged scalar stress, relative hemolysis index) must be directly traceable to the clinical endpoint (hemolysis) via a documented power-law damage accumulation model with published coefficients."
      },
      "rationale": "The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model (C=3.62×10⁻⁵, α=2.416, β=0.785) is applied to the CFD stress field to compute the relative hemolysis index. The model coefficients are sourced from peer-reviewed literature and are the same as those used in the FDA critical path study. Traceability from computational QoI to clinical endpoint is fully documented."
    },
    {
